# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: a-greek-english-lexicon
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/a-dictionary-of-first-names] The same editors also published *A Dictionary of Surnames* with OUP in 1988.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/a-greek-english-lexicon] It was most recently revised for its ninth edition of 1940.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/a-greek-english-lexicon] Abridged versions and a supplement exist.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/a-greek-english-lexicon] It was initially the basis for the 2021 *Cambridge Greek Lexicon*, although subsequently that became a complete rewrite from scratch.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/a-greek-english-lexicon] The lexicon was begun in the 19th century, and is now in its ninth (revised) edition, published in 1940.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/a-greek-english-lexicon] It was based on the earlier *Handwörterbuch der griechischen Sprache* by the German lexicographer Franz Passow (first published in 1819, fourth edition 1831), which in turn was based on Johann Gottlob Schneider's *Kritisches griechisch-deutsches Handwörterbuch*.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/a-greek-english-lexicon] The *Lexicon* has served as the basis for all later lexicographical work on the ancient Greek language, such as the ongoing Greek–Spanish dictionary project *Diccionario Griego–Español* (DGE).
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/a-greek-english-lexicon] It is now conventionally referred to as *Liddell & Scott*, *Liddell–Scott–Jones*, or *LSJ*, and its three sizes are sometimes referred to as "The Little Liddell", "The Middle Liddell" and "The Big Liddell" or "The Great Scott".
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/a-greek-english-lexicon] The LSJ main edition has 116,502 entries.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/a-greek-english-lexicon] According to Stuart Jones's preface to the ninth (1925) edition, the creation of the *Lexicon* was originally proposed by David Alphonso Talboys, an Oxford publisher.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/a-greek-english-lexicon] It was published by the Clarendon Press at Oxford rather than by Talboys, who died before the first edition (1843) was complete.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/a-greek-english-lexicon] The first editor of the LSJ, Henry George Liddell, was Dean of Christ Church, Oxford, and the father of Alice Liddell, the eponymous Alice of the writings of Lewis Carroll.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/a-greek-english-lexicon] The eighth edition (1897) was the last edition published during Liddell's lifetime.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/a-greek-english-lexicon] The LSJ is sometimes compared and contrasted with *A Latin Dictionary* by Lewis and Short, which was also published by Oxford University Press (OUP).
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/a-greek-english-lexicon] It is also sometimes compared with the Bauer lexicon, which is a similar work focused on the Greek of the New Testament.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/a-greek-english-lexicon] The LSJ's definitions reflect the Victorian morality of its time, using euphemism.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/a-greek-english-lexicon] For example, χέζω (*chezo*, 'to shit'), is translated as "ease oneself, do one's need"; βινέω (*bineo*, 'to fuck') as "inire, coire, of illicit intercourse"; and λαικάζω (*laikazo*, 'to suck cocks') as "to wench".
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/a-greek-english-lexicon] Two condensed editions of LSJ were published by Oxford University Press and remain in print.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/a-greek-english-lexicon] In 1843, the same year as the full lexicon's publication, *A Lexicon: Abridged from Liddell and Scott's Greek–English Lexicon*, sometimes called "the Little Liddell" was published.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/a-greek-english-lexicon] For example, a reprint, re-typeset in 2007, of the 1909 edition is available from Simon Wallenberg Press.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/a-greek-english-lexicon] In 1889, an intermediate edition of the lexicon, *An Intermediate Greek–English Lexicon*, was prepared on the basis of the seventh edition (1883) of LSJ.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/a-greek-english-lexicon] After the publication of the ninth edition in 1940, and shortly after the deaths of both Stuart Jones and McKenzie, the OUP maintained a list of *addenda et corrigenda* ("additions and corrections"), which was bound with subsequent printings.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/a-greek-english-lexicon] However, in 1968, these were replaced by a Supplement to the LSJ.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/a-greek-english-lexicon] Neither the *addenda* nor the Supplement has ever been merged into the main text, which still stands as originally composed by Liddell, Scott, Jones, and McKenzie.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/a-greek-english-lexicon] The Supplement was initially edited by M.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/a-greek-english-lexicon] Glare, editor of the *Oxford Latin Dictionary* (not to be confused with Lewis and Short's *A Latin Dictionary*).
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/a-greek-english-lexicon] Since 1988, it has been edited by Glare and Anne A.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/a-greek-english-lexicon] As the title page of the *Lexicon* makes clear (and the prefaces to the main text and to the Supplement attest), this editorial work has been performed "with the cooperation of many scholars".
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/a-greek-english-lexicon] The Supplement primarily takes the form of a list of additions and corrections to the main text, sorted by entry.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/a-greek-english-lexicon] The supplemental entries are marked with signs to show the nature of the changes they call for.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/a-greek-english-lexicon] Thus, a user of the *Lexicon* can consult the Supplement after consulting the main text to see whether scholarship after Jones and McKenzie has provided any new information about a particular word.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/a-greek-english-lexicon] As of 2005, the most recent revision of the Supplement, published in 1996, contains 320 pages of corrections to the main text, as well as other materials.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/a-greek-english-lexicon] The small "x" indicates that this word did not appear in the main text at all; "S.*fr*." refers to the collected fragmentary works of Sophocles.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/a-greek-english-lexicon] One interesting new source of lexicographic material in the revised Supplement is the Mycenean inscriptions.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/a-greek-english-lexicon] The ninth edition of LSJ has been freely available in electronic form since 2007, having been digitized by the Perseus Project.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/a-greek-english-lexicon] Diogenes, a free software package, incorporates the Perseus data and allows easy offline consultation of LSJ on Mac OS X, Windows, and Linux platforms.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/a-greek-english-lexicon] Marcion is another open source application that includes the Perseus LSJ.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/a-greek-english-lexicon] For mobile devices, both the Kindle E-Ink and the iPhone/iPod Touch feature data ported from Perseus.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/a-greek-english-lexicon] The Android market also currently offers the intermediate LSJ as an offline downloadable app for free or for a small price.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/a-greek-english-lexicon] A CD-ROM version published and sold by Logos Bible Software also incorporates the Supplement's additions to the ninth edition of LSJ.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/a-greek-english-lexicon] A new online version of LSJ was released in 2011 by the Thesaurus Linguae Graecae (TLG).
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/a-greek-english-lexicon] The TLG version corrects "a large number of typographical errors", and includes links to the extensive TLG textual corpus.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/a-greek-english-lexicon] A Kindle version, the "Complete Liddell & Scott's Lexicon with Inflections", is also available: it allows searches of most Classical Greek word-forms and supports a growing number of Ancient/Classical Greek texts for the device.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/a-greek-english-lexicon] The Lexicon has been translated into Modern Greek by Xenophon Moschos, ed.: Michael Konstantinidis and was published by Anestis Konstantinidis in 1904 with the title *H.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/a-greek-english-lexicon] Scott – Α.* Κωνσταντινίδου (Μέγα Λεξικόν τῆς Ἑλληνικῆς Γλώσσης).
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/a-greek-english-lexicon] Also, a supplement compiled by a group of Greek philologists.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/a-greek-english-lexicon] An Italian translation of the *Intermediate Liddell-Scott*, entitled *Dizionario illustrato Greco-Italiano* was published in 1975 by Le Monnier, edited by Q.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/a-greek-english-lexicon] LSJ was the basis of the project of John Chadwick and James Diggle at Cambridge to publish the *Cambridge Greek Lexicon* of 2021.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/a-greek-english-lexicon] Although it was initially conceived as a mere update of LSJ, the editors eventually decided to start afresh since they considered LSJ "too antiquated in concept, design and content".
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/a-greek-english-lexicon] The CGL has a smaller scope than the LSJ (and also the *Brill Dictionary of Ancient Greek*), and is unlikely to replace it; however, it is still more comprehensive than the Middle Liddell, which it intends to replace.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/a-greek-english-lexicon] The *Cambridge Greek Lexicon* uses contemporary language for its definitions and, unlike the LSJ, no longer elides the meaning of words considered offensive in Victorian times.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/a-latin-dictionary] The work is usually referred to as *Lewis and Short* after the names of its editors, Charlton T.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/a-latin-dictionary] It was derived from the 1850 English translation by Ethan Allen Andrews of an earlier Latin–German dictionary, *Wörterbuch der Lateinischen Sprache*, by the German philologist Wilhelm Freund, in turn based on I.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/a-latin-dictionary] Scheller’s Latin–German dictionary of 1783.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/a-latin-dictionary] The Andrews translation was partially revised by Freund himself, then by Henry Drisler, and was finally edited by Short and Lewis.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/a-latin-dictionary] The division of labour between the two editors was remarkably unequal.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/a-latin-dictionary] In 1890 Lewis published a heavily abridged version of the dictionary, entitled *An Elementary Latin Dictionary*, for the use of students.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/a-latin-dictionary] Sometimes called the *Elementary Lewis*, it is still in print today.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/a-latin-dictionary] The adoption of the book by Oxford University Press was the result of the failure of its own project to create a new Latin–English dictionary in 1875.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/a-latin-dictionary] Henry Nettleship and John Mayor had been commissioned to produce a new Latin dictionary based on a fresh reading of the sources, but after Mayor withdrew from the project, Nettleship was unable to complete it on his own; he eventually published his research as notes on Lewis and Short.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/a-latin-dictionary] While the Press had earlier published John Riddle's 1835 translation of Scheller's Latin–German dictionary, this was a much more expensive book.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/a-latin-dictionary] The Press thus adopted *Harpers' Latin Dictionary* as a stopgap measure, paying Harper and Brothers 10 per cent royalties.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/a-latin-dictionary] Harper and Brothers sold its rights to the American Book Company in 1899, shortly before its bankruptcy.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/a-latin-dictionary] From the time of its publication, many scholars have criticized the dictionary for its errors and inconsistencies.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/a-latin-dictionary] Because of various circumstances, however, no replacement was attempted until 1933, with the *Oxford Latin Dictionary*, which was completed in 1983.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/a-latin-dictionary] However, the *Oxford Latin Dictionary* stops at 200CE.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/a-latin-dictionary] The dictionary's full text (year 1879) is available online at numerous websites.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/a-latin-dictionary] Among classicists "never a very good dictionary", Lewis and Short has been largely superseded by the *Oxford Latin Dictionary*, called the *OLD* for short.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/a-latin-dictionary] Lewis and Short incorporated material from existing Latin dictionaries; the *OLD*, by contrast, started from scratch, following procedures similar to those of the well-regarded *Oxford English Dictionary*.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/a-latin-dictionary] Thanks to the increased availability of modern editions, the *OLD* editors had access to a larger variety of classical works.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/a-latin-dictionary] It was decided in the *OLD'*s planning that the *OLD* would not encompass Latin written later than AD 200, with a few exceptions.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/a-latin-dictionary] Although classicists still consult Lewis and Short, they tend to prefer the *OLD*.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/a-latin-dictionary] Lewis and Short retains value for its refined sense of the nuances of English diction as it interfaces with Latin diction (in contrast with *OLD*'s preference for plainer diction) and also for the sensitivity of its quotations from classical texts, reflecting this.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/a-latin-dictionary] Lewis and Short's primary focus is on classical Latin, not medieval Latin.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/a-latin-dictionary] Nevertheless, Lewis and Short is consulted by medievalists, renaissance specialists, and early modernists, as it includes some late and medieval Latin, if somewhat inconsistently, and classical Latin usages are very relevant in medieval Latin.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/a-latin-dictionary] The *Dictionary of Medieval Latin from British Sources* supplements Lewis and Short for medieval Latin vocabulary.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/a-latin-dictionary] Another dictionary focused on medieval Latin is J.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/a-latin-dictionary] Niermeyer's **Mediae Latinitatis Lexicon Minus**, first published in 1976, with an enhanced second edition in year 2002, about 1500 pages.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/a-latin-dictionary] On occasion people confuse Lewis and Short (or L&S) with Liddell and Scott, its Greek counterpart, entitled *A Greek–English Lexicon*.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/a-latin-dictionary] The 1925 and later editions of Liddell and Scott are commonly referred to by the abbreviation *LSJ* after the names of its editors Liddell, Scott and the editor of the 1925 revision, Henry Stuart Jones.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/aeolic-greek] The Aeolic dialect shows many archaisms in comparison to the other Ancient Greek dialects (Arcadocypriot, Attic, Ionic, and Doric), as well as many innovations; it is, consequently, considered to be—for the modern reader—perhaps the most difficult of the dialects.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/aeolic-greek] Aeolic Greek is widely known as the language of Sappho and of Alcaeus of Mytilene.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/aeolic-greek] Aeolic poetry, which is exemplified in the works of Sappho, mostly uses four classical meters known as the Aeolics: Glyconic (the most basic form of Aeolic line), hendecasyllabic verse, Sapphic stanza, and Alcaic stanza (the latter two are respectively named for Sappho and Alcaeus).
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/aeolic-greek] Other scholars have suggested an Aeolic Greek classification with strong Northwest Greek influence for the ancient Macedonian dialect.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/aeolic-greek] Hellanicus of Lesbos considered Makedon to be a son of Aeolus (son of Hellen).
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/aeolic-greek] Proto-Indo-European and Proto-Greek **kʷ* changed to Aeolic *p* everywhere.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/aeolic-greek] By contrast, PIE **kʷ* changed to Attic/Ionic, Arcadocypriot, and Doric *t* before *e* and *i*.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/aeolic-greek] Similarly PIE/PGk **gʷ* always became *b* and PIE **gʷʰ* > PGk **kʰʷ* always became *ph* (whereas in other dialects they became alternating *b*/*d* and *ph*/*th* before back/front vowels).
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/aeolic-greek] Labiovelars were treated the same way in the P-Celtic languages and the Sabellic languages.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/aeolic-greek] A Proto-Greek consonant cluster with *h* (from Indo-European **s*) and a sonorant (*r, l, n, m, w, y*) changed to the double sonorant (*rr, ll, nn, mm, ww, yy*) in Lesbian and Thessalian (sub-dialects of Aeolic) by assimilation.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/aeolic-greek] In Attic/Ionic, Doric, and Boeotian Aeolic, the *h* assimilated to the vowel before the consonant cluster, causing the vowel to lengthen by compensatory lengthening.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/aeolic-greek] Lesbian Aeolic lost initial *h-* (*psilosis* "stripping") from Proto-Indo-European *s- or *y-.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/aeolic-greek] By contrast, Ionic sometimes retains it, and Attic always retains it.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/aeolic-greek] In Thessalian and Boeotian (sub-dialects of Aeolic) and Doric, the Proto-Indo-European and Proto-Greek semi-vowel *w* (digamma) was retained at the beginning of a word.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/aeolic-greek] In Aeolic and Doric, Proto-Greek long *ā* remains.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/aeolic-greek] By contrast, in Attic, long *ā* changes to long *ē* in most cases; in Ionic, it changes everywhere.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/aeolic-greek] Compensatory lengthening of *a, e, o* in Lesbian gives *ai, ei, oi* (in Attic, it would be *ā, ei, ou*) for example in the accusative plural of a and o stem nouns, or in many 3 Pl verb conjugations.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/aeolic-greek] In Boeotian, the vowel-system was, in many cases, changed in a way reminiscent of the modern Greek pronunciation.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/aeolic-greek] In Lesbian Aeolic, the accent of all words is recessive (*barytonesis*), as is typical only in the verbs of other dialects.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/aeolic-greek] Contracted or vowel-stem verbs that are thematic in Attic/Ionic are often athematic (*-mi*) in Aeolic.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/aeolic-greek] Aeolic athematic infinitive active ends in *-men* or (Lesbian) *-menai*. ~ Attic/Ionic has *-enai*.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/aeolic-greek] In the Lesbian dialect this ending also extends to the thematic conjugation, where Attic/Ionic has *-ein*.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/aeolic-greek] All three of these Aeolic endings occur in Homer.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/aeolic-greek] Proto-Greek *-ans* and *-ons* → *-ais* and *-ois* (first- and second declension accusative plural) ~ Attic/Ionic -*ās* and *-ōs* (-ους).
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/aeolic-greek] Dative plural *-aisi* and *-oisi* ~ Attic/Ionic *-ais* and *-ois*.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/aeolic-greek] The participle has *-ois* and *-ais* for Attic *-ōs* (-ους), *-ās*.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/aeolic-greek] Below is a list of several words in the Aeolian dialect, written in the Greek alphabet, along with a transcription in the Latin alphabet.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/aeolic-greek] Each word is followed by its meaning and compared to similar words in other ancient Greek dialects.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/aeolic-greek] The "notes" section provides additional information, and if applicable, an etymology is given.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] The character originated in stories told by Carroll to entertain the Liddell sisters while rowing on the Isis with his friend Robinson Duckworth, and on subsequent rowing trips.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] Although she shares her given name with Alice Liddell, scholars disagree about the extent to which she was based upon Liddell.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] Characterized by Carroll as "loving and gentle", "courteous to all", "trustful", and "wildly curious", Alice has been variously seen as clever, well-mannered, and sceptical of authority, although some commentators find more negative aspects of her personality.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] Her appearance changed from *Alice's Adventures Under Ground*, the first draft of *Alice's Adventures in Wonderland*, to political cartoonist John Tenniel's illustrations of her in the two *Alice* books.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] Alice has been identified as a cultural icon.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] She has been described as a departure from the usual nineteenth-century child protagonist, and the success of the two *Alice* books inspired numerous sequels, parodies, and imitations, with protagonists similar to Alice in temperament.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] She has been interpreted through various critical approaches, and has appeared and been re-imagined in numerous adaptations, including Walt Disney's film (1951).
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] Her continuing appeal has been ascribed to her ability to be continuously re-imagined.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] Alice is a fictional child living during the middle of the Victorian era.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] In *Alice's Adventures in Wonderland* (1865), which takes place on 4 May, the character is widely assumed to be seven years old; Alice gives her age as seven and a half in the sequel, which takes place on 4 November.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] In the text of the two *Alice* books, author Lewis Carroll often did not remark on the physical appearance of his protagonist.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] Details of her fictional life can be discovered from the text of the two books.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] At home, she has a significantly older sister, a brother, a pet cat named Dinah, an elderly nurse, and a governess, who teaches her lessons starting at nine in the morning.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] Additionally, she had gone to a day school at some point in her backstory.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] Alice has been variously characterised as belonging to the upper class, middle class, or part of the bourgeoisie.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] The degree to which the character of Alice can be identified as Alice Liddell is controversial.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] Some critics identify the character as Liddell, or write that she inspired the character.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] Others argue that Carroll considered his protagonist and Liddell to be separate.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] According to Carroll, his character was not based on any real child, but was entirely fictional.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] Alice debuted in Carroll's first draft of *Alice's Adventures in Wonderland*, *Alice's Adventures Under Ground*.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] *Under Ground* originated from stories told to the Liddell sisters during an afternoon on 4 July 1862 while rowing on the Isis with his friend Robinson Duckworth, and on subsequent rowing trips.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] At the request of ten-year-old Alice Liddell, Carroll wrote down the stories as *Alice's Adventures Under Ground*, which he completed in February 1864.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] *Under Ground* contains thirty-seven illustrations, twenty-seven of which Alice is depicted in.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] As his drawings of Alice bear little physical resemblance to Alice Liddell, whose given name she shares, it has been suggested that Alice's younger sister, Edith, might have been his model.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] Carroll portrays his protagonist as wearing a tunic, in contrast to the tailored dresses that the Liddell sisters might have worn.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] His illustrations drew influence from the Pre-Raphaelite painters Dante Gabriel Rossetti and Arthur Hughes, whose painting *The Lady with the Lilacs* (1863) he visually alluded to in one drawing in *Under Ground*.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] He gave the hand-written *Alice's Adventures Under Ground* to Alice Liddell in November 1864.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] John Tenniel illustrated *Alice's Adventures in Wonderland* (1865) for a fee of £138, which was roughly a fourth of what Carroll earned each year and which he paid for himself.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] Tenniel was an already successful, well-known lead illustrator for the satirical magazine *Punch*, when Carroll employed him as an illustrator in April 1864.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] In contrast, Carroll did not have any literary fame at the time.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] Tenniel likely based the majority of his illustrations on those in *Under Ground*, and Carroll carefully oversaw his work; among his suggestions was that Alice should have long, light-coloured hair.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] Alice's clothes are typical of what a girl belonging to the middle class in the mid-Victorian era might have worn at home.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] Her pinafore, a detail created by Tenniel and now associated with the character, "suggests a certain readiness for action and lack of ceremony".
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] Tenniel's depiction of Alice has its origins in a physically similar character which appeared in at least eight cartoons in *Punch*, during a four-year period that began in 1860.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] In an 1860 cartoon, this character wore clothes now associated with Alice: "the full skirt, pale stockings, flat shoes, and a hairband over her loose hair".
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] In the cartoons, the character appeared as an archetype of a pleasant girl from the middle classes; she has been described as similar to Alice: "a pacifist and noninterventionist, patient and polite, slow to return the aggression of others".
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] Tenniel's fee for illustrating the sequel *Through the Looking-Glass* (1871) rose to £290, which Carroll again paid for out of his own pocket.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] Tenniel changed Alice's clothing slightly in the sequel, where she wears horizontal-striped stockings instead of plain ones and has a more ornate pinafore with a bow.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] Originally, Alice wore a "crinoline-supported chessmanlike skirt" similar to that of the Red and White Queens, as a queen; the design was rejected by Carroll.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] Her clothing as a queen and in the railway carriage is a polonaise-styled dress with a bustle, which would have been fashionable at the time.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] The clothing worn by the characters in *My First Sermon* (1863) by pre-Raphaelite painter John Millais and "The Travelling Companions" (1862) by Victorian painter Augustus Leopold Egg have some elements in common with Alice's clothing in the railway carriage.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] Carroll expressed unhappiness at Tenniel's refusal to use a model for illustrations of Alice, writing that this resulted in her head and feet being out of proportion.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] In February 1881, Carroll contacted his publisher about the possibility of creating *The Nursery "Alice"*, a simplified edition of *Alice's Adventures in Wonderland* with coloured and enlarged illustrations.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] Tenniel coloured twenty illustrations from *Alice's Adventures in Wonderland*, in addition to revising some aspects of them; Alice is depicted as a blonde, and her dress is yellow, with blue stockings.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] Her dress became pleated with a bow at the back of it, and she wore a bow in her hair.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] Edmund Evans printed the illustrations in colour through chromoxylography, a process using woodblocks to produce colour prints.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] Alice has been recognised as a cultural icon.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] The *Alice* books have continued to remain in print, and the first book is available in a hundred languages.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] *Alice's Adventures in Wonderland* has continued to maintain its popularity, placing on surveys of the top children's books.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] Alice placed on a 2015 British survey of the top twenty favorite characters in children's literature.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] She also lends her name to the style of headband that she is depicted with in Tenniel's illustrations.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] The continued popularity of the two *Alice* books has resulted in numerous adaptations, re-imaginings, literary continuations, and various merchandise.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] From the 1930s to 1940s, the books came under the scrutiny of psychoanalytic literary critics.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] Freudians believed that the events in *Alice's Adventures in Wonderland* reflected the personality and desires of the author, because the stories which it was based on had been told spontaneously.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] In 1933, Anthony Goldschmidt introduced "the modern idea of Carroll as a repressed sexual deviant", theorizing that Alice served as Carroll's representation in the novel; Goldschmidt's influential work, however, may have been meant as a hoax.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] Regardless, Freudian analysis found in the books symbols of "classic Freudian tropes": "a vaginal rabbit hole and a phallic Alice, an amniotic pool of tears, hysterical mother figures and impotent father figures, threats of decapitation [castration], swift identity changes".
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] Described as "the single greatest rival of Tenniel," Walt Disney created an influential representation of Alice in his 1951 film adaptation, which helped to mould the image of Alice within pop culture.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] Although Alice had previously been depicted as a blonde in a blue dress in an unauthorised American edition of the two *Alice* books published by Thomas Crowell (1893), possibly for the first time, Disney's portrayal has been the most influential in solidifying the popular image of Alice as such.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] Disney's version of Alice has its visual basis in Mary Blair's concept drawings and Tenniel's illustrations.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] While the film was not successful during its original run, it later became popular with college students, who interpreted the film as a drug-drenched narrative.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] In 1974, *Alice in Wonderland* was re-released in the United States, with advertisements playing off this association.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] The drug association persists as an "unofficial" interpretation, despite the film's status as family-friendly entertainment.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] In the twenty-first century, Alice's continuing appeal has been attributed to her ability to be continuously re-imagined.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] In Japan, Alice has a significant influence on pop culture.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] Tenniel's artwork and Disney's film adaptation have been credited as factors in the continuing favorable reception of the two novels.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] Within youth culture in Japan, she has been adopted as "a rebellion figure in much the same way as the American and British 1960s 'hippies' did." She has also been a source of inspiration for Japanese fashion, in particular Lolita fashion.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] The two *Alice* books are frequently re-illustrated.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] The expiration of the copyright of *Alice's Adventures in Wonderland* in 1907 resulted in eight new printings, including one illustrated in an Art Nouveau style by Arthur Rackham.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] The illustrators for the other editions published in 1907 include Charles Robinson, Alice Ross, W.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] Walker, Thomas Maybank and Millicent Sowerby.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] Among the other notable illustrators are Blanche McManus (1896); Peter Newell (1901), who used monochrome; Mabel Lucie Atwell (1910); Harry Furniss (1926); and Willy Pogany (1929), who featured an Art Deco style.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] Notable illustrators from the 1930s onwards include Edgar Thurstan (1931), and his visual allusions to the Wall Street crash of 1929; D.R.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] Morton Sale (1933), both of whom featured an older Alice; Mervyn Peake (1954); Ralph Steadman (1967), for which he received the Francis Williams Memorial award in 1972; Salvador Dalí (1969), who used Surrealism; and Peter Blake, with his watercolours (1970).
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-alice-s-adventures-in-wonderland] By 1972, there were ninety illustrators of *Alice's Adventures in Wonderland* and twenty-one of *Through the Looking-Glass*.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-liddell] Alice Liddell was the fourth of the ten children of Henry Liddell, Dean of Christ Church, Oxford, one of the editors of *A Greek-English Lexicon*, and his wife Lorina Hanna Liddell (*née* Reeve).
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-liddell] She had two older brothers, Harry (born 1847) and Arthur (1850–53), an older sister Lorina (born 1849), and six younger siblings, including her sister Edith (born 1854) to whom she was very close, and her brother Frederick (born 1865).
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-liddell] At the time of her birth, her father was the Headmaster of Westminster School, but soon afterwards he was appointed to the deanery of Christ Church, Oxford.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-liddell] The Liddell family moved to Oxford in 1856.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-liddell] Soon after this move, Alice met Charles Lutwidge Dodgson (Lewis Carroll), who encountered the family while photographing the cathedral on 25 April 1856.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-liddell] He became a close friend of the Liddell family in subsequent years.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-liddell] Alice was three years younger than Lorina and two years older than Edith, and the three sisters were constant childhood companions.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-liddell] She and her family regularly spent holidays at their holiday home, Penmorfa, which later became the Gogarth Abbey Hotel, on the West Shore of Llandudno in North Wales.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-liddell] When Alice was a young woman, she set out on a Grand Tour of Europe with Lorina and Edith.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-liddell] One story has it that she became a romantic interest of Prince Leopold, the youngest son of Queen Victoria, during the four years he spent at Christ Church, but the evidence for this is sparse.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-liddell] It is true that years later, Leopold named his first child Alice and acted as godfather to Alice's second son, Leopold.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-liddell] However, it is possible Alice was instead named in honour of Leopold's deceased elder sister, the Grand Duchess of Hesse.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-liddell] A recent biographer of Leopold suggests it is far more likely that Alice's sister Edith was the true recipient of Leopold's attention.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-liddell] Edith died on 26 June 1876, possibly of measles or peritonitis (accounts differ), shortly before she was to be married to Aubrey Harcourt, a cricket player.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-liddell] Prince Leopold served as a pall-bearer at her funeral on 30 June 1876.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-liddell] Alice Liddell married Reginald Hargreaves, also a cricketer, on 15 September 1880, at the age of 28, in Westminster Abbey.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-liddell] They had three sons: Alan Knyveton Hargreaves and Leopold Reginald "Rex" Hargreaves (both were killed in action in World War I); and Caryl Liddell Hargreaves, who survived to have a daughter of his own.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-liddell] Liddell denied that the name 'Caryl' was in any way associated with Charles Dodgson's pseudonym.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-liddell] Reginald Hargreaves inherited a considerable fortune and was a local magistrate; he also played cricket for Hampshire.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-liddell] Alice became a noted society hostess and was the first president of Emery Down Women's Institute.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-liddell] During World War I, she joined the Red Cross as a volunteer, for which she was awarded a medal currently on display in the Museum of Oxford.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-liddell] She took to referring to herself as "Lady Hargreaves", but no basis existed for such a title.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-liddell] For most of her life, Alice lived in and around Lyndhurst in the New Forest, in the county of Hampshire.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-liddell] With her husband's death in 1926, the cost of maintaining their home, Cuffnells, was such that she deemed it necessary to sell her copy of *Alice's Adventures under Ground* (Lewis Carroll's earlier title for *Alice's Adventures in Wonderland*).
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-liddell] The manuscript fetched £15,400 (equivalent to £800,000 in 2025), nearly four times the reserve price given to it by Sotheby's auction house.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-liddell] It later became the possession of Eldridge R.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-liddell] Johnson and was displayed at Columbia University on the centennial of Carroll's birth in 1932.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-liddell] Alice was present, aged 80, and it was on this visit to the United States that she met Peter Llewelyn Davies, one of the brothers who inspired J.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-liddell] After Johnson's death in 1945, the book was purchased by a consortium of American bibliophiles and presented to the British people "in recognition of Britain's courage in facing Hitler".
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-liddell] The manuscript is held by the British Library.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-liddell] After she died in 1934, her body was cremated at Golders Green Crematorium, with her ashes being buried in the graveyard of the church of St Michael and All Angels in Lyndhurst, Hampshire.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-liddell] Alice's mirror can be found on display at the New Forest Heritage Centre, Lyndhurst, a free museum sharing the history of the New Forest National Park.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-liddell] On 4 July 1862, in a rowing boat travelling on the Isis from Folly Bridge, Oxford, to Godstow for a picnic outing, 10-year-old Alice asked Charles Dodgson (who wrote under the pen name Lewis Carroll) to entertain her and her sisters, Edith (aged 8) and Lorina (13), with a story.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-liddell] As the Reverend Robinson Duckworth rowed the boat, Dodgson regaled the girls with fantastic stories of a girl named Alice and her adventures after she fell into a rabbit-hole.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-liddell] The story was not unlike those Dodgson had spun for the sisters before, but this time Liddell asked Dodgson to write it down for her.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-liddell] He promised to do so but did not get around to the task for some months.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-liddell] He eventually presented her with the manuscript of *Alice's Adventures Under Ground* in November 1864.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-liddell] In the meantime, Dodgson had decided to rewrite the story as a possible commercial venture.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-liddell] Probably with a view to canvassing his opinion, Dodgson sent the manuscript of *Under Ground* to a friend, the author George MacDonald, in early 1863.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-liddell] The MacDonald children read the story and loved it, and this response probably persuaded Dodgson to seek a publisher.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-liddell] *Alice's Adventures in Wonderland*, with illustrations by John Tenniel, was published in 1865, under the name Lewis Carroll.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-liddell] A second book about the character Alice, *Through the Looking-Glass and What Alice Found There*, followed in 1871.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-liddell] In 1886, a facsimile of *Alice's Adventures Under Ground*, the original manuscript that Dodgson had given Liddell, was published.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-liddell] The relationship between Liddell and Dodgson has been the source of much controversy.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-liddell] Dodgson met the Liddell family in 1855; he first befriended Harry, the older brother, and later took Harry and Ina on several boating trips and picnics to the scenic areas around Oxford.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-liddell] Later, when Harry went to school, Alice and her younger sister Edith joined the party.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-liddell] Dodgson entertained the children by telling them fantastic stories to while away the time.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-liddell] He also used them as subjects for his hobby, photography.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-liddell] It has often been stated that Alice was his favourite subject in these years, but there is very little evidence to suggest this; Dodgson's diaries from 18 April 1858 to 8 May 1862 are missing.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-liddell] The relationship between the Liddells and Dodgson suffered a sudden break in June 1863.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-liddell] There was no record of why the rift occurred, since the Liddells never openly spoke of it, and the single page in Dodgson's diary recording 27–29 June 1863 (which seems to cover the period in which it began) was missing; it has been speculated by biographers such as Morton N.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-liddell] Cohen that Dodgson may have wanted to marry the 11-year-old Alice Liddell, and that this was the cause of the unexplained break with the family in June 1863.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-liddell] In 1996, Karoline Leach found what became known as the "Cut pages in diary" document—a note allegedly written by Dodgson's niece, Violet Dodgson, summarising the missing page from 27 to 29 June 1863, apparently written before she (or her sister Menella) removed the page.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-liddell] This might imply that the break between Dodgson and the Liddell family was caused by concern over alleged gossip linking Dodgson to the family governess and to "Ina" (both Alice's older sister and her mother were named "Lorina").
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-liddell] In her biography, *The Mystery of Lewis Carroll,* Jenny Woolf suggests that the problem was caused by Lorina becoming too attached to Dodgson and not the other way around.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-liddell] Leach has said that the handwriting on the front of the document most closely resembles that of either Menella or Violet Dodgson, Dodgson's nieces.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-liddell] Cohen in an article published in the *Times Literary Supplement* in 2003 said that in the 1960s, Dodgson's great-nephew Philip Dodgson Jacques told him that Jacques had written the note himself based on conversations he remembered with Dodgson's nieces.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-liddell] Cohen's article offered no evidence to support this, however, and known samples of Jacques' handwriting do not seem to resemble the writing of the note.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-liddell] After this incident, Dodgson avoided the Liddell home for six months but eventually returned for a visit in December 1863.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-liddell] However, the former closeness does not seem to have been re-established, and the friendship gradually faded away, possibly because Dodgson was in opposition to Dean Liddell over college politics.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-liddell] The extent to which Dodgson's *Alice* may be or could be identified with Liddell is controversial.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-liddell] The two Alices are clearly not identical, and though it was long assumed that the fictional Alice was based very heavily on Liddell, recent research has contradicted this assumption.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-liddell] Dodgson himself claimed in later years that his Alice was entirely imaginary and not based upon any real child at all.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-liddell] There was a rumour that Dodgson sent Tenniel a photo of one of his other child-friends, Mary Hilton Badcock, suggesting that he use her as a model, but attempts to find documentary support for this theory have proved fruitless.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-liddell] Dodgson's own drawings of the character in the original manuscript of *Alice's Adventures Under Ground* show little resemblance to Liddell.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-liddell] Biographer Anne Clark suggests that Dodgson might have used Edith Liddell as a model for his drawings.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-liddell] There are at least four direct links to Liddell in the two books.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-liddell] First, he set them on 4 May (Liddell's birthday) and 4 November (her "half-birthday"), and in *Through the Looking-Glass* the fictional Alice declares that her age is "seven and a half exactly", the same as Liddell on that date.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-liddell] Second, he dedicated them "to Alice Pleasance Liddell".
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-liddell] Also the name "Lacie" is an anagram of "Alice", while "Elsie" refers to Lorina, whose second name was Charlotte, giving her the initials L.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-liddell] "Tillie" refers to Edith's family nickname of "Matilda".
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-liddell] Fourth, there is an acrostic poem at the end of *Through the Looking-Glass*.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-liddell] Reading downward, taking the first letter of each line, spells out Liddell's full name.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-liddell] The poem has no title in *Through the Looking-Glass*, but is usually referred to by its first line, "A Boat Beneath a Sunny Sky".
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/alice-liddell] In addition, all of those who participated in the Thames boating expedition where the story was originally told (Carroll, Duckworth, and the three Liddell sisters) appear in the chapter "A Caucus-Race and a Long Tale" – but only if Alice Liddell is represented by Alice herself.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] In 2004, Amazon founder and CEO Jeff Bezos instructed the company's employees to build the world's best electronic reader before Amazon's competitors could.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] Amazon originally used the codename *Fiona* for the device.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] Branding consultants Michael Cronan and Karin Hibma devised the Kindle name.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] Lab126 asked them to name the product, and they suggested "kindle", meaning to light a fire.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] They felt this was an apt metaphor for reading and intellectual excitement.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] Kindle hardware evolved from the original Kindle introduced in 2007 and the Kindle DX (with its larger 9.7" screen) introduced in 2009.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] The DX remained the only non-6" E Ink Kindle device until the 2017 introduction of the Oasis 2.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] However, the Kindle e-reader has often been a narrow-purpose device for reading rather than being multipurpose hardware that might create distractions while reading.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] Active Content support was introduced in 2010 only to be dropped from new Kindle devices in late 2014.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] After the first three generations, the Kindle Fire tablet branding was changed to Amazon Fire in 2014; this name change reflected their wider capabilities as an Android-derived tablet.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] Other later developments include devices with larger E Ink displays such as the Kindle Oasis 2 (2017) at 7" and the Paperwhite 5 (2021) at 6.8", as well as a device with a 10.2" screen and Wacom stylus support called the Kindle Scribe (2022).
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] In 2022 Amazon also introduced the 11th gen Kindle with a 300 PPI display, ending the use of the 6" 167 PPI display that had been on every basic Kindle since 2007.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] In 2024 Amazon introduced the first color E Ink Kindle, the Kindle Colorsoft Signature Edition.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] In 2025 Amazon updated the Scribe lineup with a new design and introduced a Scribe Colorsoft model.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] Amazon has also released Kindle apps for a wide range of devices and platforms, including Windows, macOS, Android, iOS, BlackBerry 10 and Windows Phone.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] Amazon also has a cloud reader to allow users to read e-books using modern web browsers.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] Kindle devices support dictionary and Wikipedia look-up functions when highlighting a word in an e-book.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] The font type, size and margins can be customized.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] Kindles are charged by connecting to a computer's USB port or to an AC adapter.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] Users needing accessibility due to impaired vision can use an audio adapter to listen to any e-book read aloud on supported Kindles, or those with difficulty in reading text may use the Amazon Ember Bold font for darker text and other fonts may too have bold font versions.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] It also includes other fonts for accessibility like OpenDyslexic.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] The Kindle also contains experimental features such as a web browser that uses NetFront based on WebKit.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] The browser can freely access the Kindle Store and Wikipedia on 3G models while the browser may be limited to 50 MB of data per month to websites other than Amazon and Wikipedia.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] Other possible experimental features, depending on the model are a *Text-to-Speech* engine that can read the text from e-books and an MP3 player that can be used to play music while reading.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] The Kindle's operating system updates are designed to be received wirelessly and installed automatically during a period in sleep mode in which Wi-Fi is turned on.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] A user may install firmware updates manually by downloading the firmware for their device and copying the file to the device's root directory.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] The Kindle operating system uses the Linux kernel with a Java app for reading e-books.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] Amazon initially offered a Personal Documents Service to add content to a user's Kindle which only worked via email.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] Documents were sent directly to the Kindle via WhisperSync.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] Later expansions added cloud library features and content management.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] The modern service is called Send to Kindle and is available through various means such as email, website, app, or browser extension.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] It allows the user to send files such as EPUB, PDF, HTML pages, Microsoft Word documents, GIF, PNG, and BMP graphics directly to the user's Kindle library.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] When Amazon receives the file, it converts the file to Kindle File Format and stores it in the user's online library (called "Your Content" by Amazon).
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] Content added via Send to Kindle is added to the user library as Personal Documents by default, but some Send to Kindle interfaces allow users to send a document to a specific device and skip adding it to the library.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] The Send to Kindle service's personal documents can be accessed by all Kindle hardware devices as well as iOS and Android devices using the Kindle app.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] Until August 2022, in addition to the document types mentioned above, this service could be used to send unprotected and original version only .mobi/.azw files to a user's Kindle library.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] Sending the file is free if downloaded using Wi-Fi, but, prior to 2021, cost $0.15 per MB when using Kindle's former 3G service.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] The first Kindle could read unprotected Mobipocket files (MOBI, PRC), plain text files (TXT), Topaz format books (TPZ) and Amazon's AZW format.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] The Kindle 2 added native PDF capability with the version 2.3 firmware upgrade.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] The Kindle 1 could not read PDF files, but Amazon provides experimental conversion to the native AZW format, with the caveat that not all PDFs may format correctly.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] The Kindle 2 added the ability to play the Audible Enhanced (AAX) format.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] The Kindle 2 can also display HTML files.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] The fourth and later generation Kindles, Touch, Paperwhite (all generations), Voyage and Oasis (all generations) can display AZW, AZW3, TXT, PDF, unprotected MOBI, and PRC files natively.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] HTML, DOC, DOCX, JPEG, GIF, PNG, and BMP are usable through Amazon's conversion service.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] The Keyboard, Touch, Oasis 2 & 3, Kindle 8 & 9, and Paperwhite 4 can also play Audible Enhanced (AA, AAX).
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] All Kindle models from the Kindle Paperwhite 2 and newer can display KFX files natively.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] KFX is Amazon's successor to the AZW3 format.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] Kindles cannot natively display EPUB files.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] Kindles can be jailbroken to allow third-party software, such as KOReader which does support EPUB, to be installed.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] In late April 2022, Amazon announced that Send to Kindle would support EPUB, beginning in late 2022.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] An e-book may be downloaded from Amazon to several devices at the same time, as long as the devices are registered to the same Amazon account.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] A sharing limit typically ranges from one to six devices, depending on an undisclosed number of licenses set by the publisher.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] When a limit is reached, the user must remove the e-book from some device or unregister a device containing the e-book in order to add the e-book to another device.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] The original Kindle and Kindle 2 did not allow the user to organize books into folders.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] The user could only select what type of content to display on the home screen and whether to organize by author, title, or download date.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] Kindle software version 2.5 allowed for the organization of books into "Collections" which behave like non-structured tags/labels: a collection cannot include other collections, and one book may be added to multiple collections.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] These collections are normally set and organized on the Kindle itself, one book at a time.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] Collections can also be sent from one Kindle device to another.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] There is no option to organize by series or series order, as the AZW format does not possess the necessary metadata fields.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] X-Ray is a reference tool that is incorporated in Kindle Touch and later devices, the Fire tablets, the Kindle app for mobile platforms and Fire TV.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] X-Ray lets users explore in greater depth the contents of a book, by accessing preloaded files with relevant information, such as the most common characters, locations, themes, or ideas.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] Users can bookmark, highlight, and search through content.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] Pages can be bookmarked for reference, and notes can be added to relevant content.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] While a book is open on the display, menu options allow users to search for synonyms and definitions from the built-in dictionary.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] The device also remembers the last page read for each book.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] Pages can be saved as a "clipping", or a text file containing the text of the currently displayed page.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] All clippings are appended to a single file, which can be downloaded over a USB cable.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] Due to the TXT format of the clippings file, all formatting (such as bold, italics, bigger fonts for headlines, etc.) is stripped from the original text.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] On July 18, 2011, Amazon began a program that allows college students to rent Kindle textbooks from three different publishers for a fixed period of time.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] Kindle devices may report information about their users' reading data that includes the last page read, how long each e-book was opened, annotations, bookmarks, notes, highlights, or similar markings to Amazon.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] The Kindle stores this information on all Amazon e-books but it is unclear if this data is stored for non-Amazon e-books.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] There is a lack of e-reader data privacy — Amazon knows the user's identity, what the user is reading, whether the user has finished the book, what page the user is on, how long the user has spent on each page, and which passages the user may have highlighted.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] Content from Amazon's Kindle Store is encoded in Amazon's proprietary Kindle formats (.azw, .kf8 and .kfx).
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] In addition to published content, Kindle users can also access the Internet using the experimental web browser, which uses NetFront.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] Users can use the Kindle Store to access reading material using the Kindle itself or through a web browser to access content.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] The store features Kindle Unlimited for unlimited access to over one million e-books for a monthly fee.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] Content for the Kindle can be purchased online and downloaded wirelessly in some countries, using either standard Wi-Fi or Amazon's 3G Whispernet network.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] Whispernet is accessible without any monthly fees or a subscription, although fees can be incurred for the delivery of periodicals and other content when roaming internationally beyond the customer's home country.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] Through a service called Whispersync, customers can synchronize reading progress, bookmarks, and other information across Kindle hardware and other mobile devices.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] The Kindles that only can access Whispernet via the 3G network had that network turned off in December 2021 due to the carriers retiring 3G.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] For U.S. customers traveling abroad, Amazon originally charged a $1.99 fee to download e-books over 3G while overseas, but later removed the fee.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] Fees remain for wireless 3G delivery of periodical subscriptions and personal documents, while Wi-Fi delivery has no extra charge.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] In addition to the Kindle Store, content for the Kindle can be purchased from various independent sources such as Fictionwise and Baen Ebooks.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] Public domain titles are also obtainable for the Kindle via content providers such as Project Gutenberg, The Internet Archive and the World Public Library.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] In 2011, the Kindle Store had more than twice as much paid content as its nearest competitor, Barnes & Noble.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] Public libraries that offer books via OverDrive, Inc. can also choose to lend titles for the Kindle and Kindle reading apps in the US via Libby.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] Books can be checked out from the library's own site, which forwards to Amazon for the completion of the checkout process.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] The Libby app stores user account and library details during set up and can send content to the users Amazon account at the time of checkout.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] Amazon then delivers the title to the Kindle for the duration of the loan, though some titles may require transfer via a USB connection to a computer.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] If the book is later checked out again or purchased, annotations and bookmarks are preserved.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] Amazon released the *Kindle for PC* application in late 2009, available for Microsoft Windows systems.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] This application allows ebooks from Amazon's store or personal ebooks to be read on a personal computer, with no Kindle device required.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] Amazon released a *Kindle for Mac* app for Apple Macintosh & OS X systems in early 2010.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] In June 2010, Amazon released the *Amazon Kindle for Android*.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] Soon after the Android release, versions for the Apple iOS (iPhone and iPad) and BlackBerry OS phones were available.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] In January 2011, Amazon released *Kindle for Windows Phone*.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] In July 2011, Kindle for HP TouchPad (running webOS) was released in the U.S. as a beta version.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] In August 2011, Amazon released an HTML5-based webapp for supported web browsers called *Kindle Cloud Reader*.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] In 2013, Amazon has expressed no interest in releasing a separate Kindle application for Linux systems; the Cloud Reader can be used on supported browsers in Linux.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] It is also possible to use Kindle via the Web.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] On April 17, 2014, Samsung announced it would discontinue its own e-book store effective July 1, 2014, and it partnered with Amazon to create the *Kindle for Samsung* app optimized for display on Samsung Galaxy devices.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] The app uses Amazon's e-book store and it includes a monthly limited selection of free e-books.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] In June 2016, Amazon released the Page Flip feature to its Kindle applications that debuted on its e-readers a few years previously.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] This feature allows the user to flip through nine thumbnails of page images at a time.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] Concurrently with the release of the first Kindle device, Amazon launched Kindle Direct Publishing, used by authors and publishers to independently publish their books directly to Kindle and Kindle Apps worldwide.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] Authors can upload documents in several formats for delivery via Whispernet and charge between $0.99 and $200.00 per download.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] In a December 5, 2009, interview with *The New York Times*, Amazon CEO Jeff Bezos revealed that Amazon keeps 65% of the revenue from all e-book sales for the Kindle; the remaining 35% is split between the book author and publisher.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] After numerous commentators observed that Apple's popular App Store offers 70% of royalties to the publisher, Amazon began a program that offers 70% royalties to Kindle publishers who agree to certain conditions.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] Some of these conditions, such as the inability to opt out of the lendability feature, have caused some controversy.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] On January 21, 2010, Amazon announced the release of its Kindle Development Kit (KDK).
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] KDK aims to allow developers to build "active content" for the Kindle, and a beta version was announced with a February 2010 release date.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] A number of companies have already experimented with delivering active content through the Kindle's bundled browser, and the KDK gives sample code, documentation and a Kindle Simulator together with a new revenue sharing model for developers.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] The KDK is based on the Java programming language's Personal Basis Profile packaged Java APIs.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] As of May 2014, the Kindle store offered over 400 items labeled as active content.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] These items include simple applications and games, including a free set provided by Amazon Digital Services.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] As of 2014, active content is only available to users with a U.S. billing address.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] In October 2014, Amazon announced that the Voyage and future e-readers would not support active content because most users prefer to use apps on their smartphones and tablets, but the Paperwhite first-iteration and earlier Kindles would continue to support active content.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] Specific Kindle device sales numbers are not released by Amazon; however, according to anonymous inside sources, over three million Kindles had been sold as of December 2009, while external estimates, as of Q4-2009, place the number at about 1.5 million.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] According to James McQuivey of Forrester Research, estimates are ranging around four million, as of mid-2010.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] In 2010, Amazon remained the undisputed leader in the e-reader category, accounting for 59% of e-readers shipped, and it gained 14 percentage points in share.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] According to an International Data Corporation (IDC) study from March 2011, sales for all e-book readers worldwide reached 12.8 million in 2010; 48% of them were Kindles.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] In the last three months of 2010, Amazon announced that in the United States its e-book sales had surpassed sales of paperback books for the first time.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] In January 2011, Amazon announced that digital books were outselling their traditional print counterparts for the first time ever on its site, with an average of 115 Kindle editions being sold for every 100 paperback editions.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] In December 2011, Amazon announced that customers had purchased "well over" one million Kindles per week since the end of November 2011; this includes all available Kindle models and also the Kindle Fire tablet.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] IDC estimated that the Kindle Fire sold about 4.7 million units during the fourth quarter of 2011.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] Pacific Crest estimated that the Kindle Fire models sold six million units during Q4 2012.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] Morgan Stanley estimates that Amazon sold $3.57 billion worth of Kindle e-readers and tablets in 2012, $4.5 billion in Kindle device sales in 2013 and $5 billion in Kindle device sales in 2014.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] Amazon claims that their sales had reached a decade-long high before the announcement of the 2024 models.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] Working Kindles in good condition can be sold, traded, donated or recycled in the aftermarket.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] Due to some Kindle devices being limited to use as reading device and the hassle of reselling Kindles, some people choose to donate their Kindle to schools, developing countries, literacy organizations, or charities.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] "The Kindle Classroom Project" promotes reading by distributing donated Kindles to schools in need.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] Worldreader and "Develop Africa" ships donated e-readers to schools in developing countries in Africa for educational use.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] "Project Hart" may take donations of e-readers that could be given to people in need.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] Whether in good condition or not, Kindles should not be disposed of in normal waste due to the device's electronic ink components and batteries.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] Instead, Kindles at the end of their useful life should be recycled.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] In the United States, Amazon runs their own program, 'Take Back', which allows owners to print out a prepaid shipping label, which can be used to return the device for disposal.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] The two books were protected by copyright in the United States, but they were in the public domain in Canada, Australia and other countries.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] Notes and annotations for the books made by users on their devices were left in a separate file but "rendered useless" without the content to which they were directly linked.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] Customers and commentators noted the resemblance to the censorship in the novel, and described Amazon's action in Orwellian terms.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] Bezos said the action was "stupid", and that the executives at Amazon "deserve the criticism received".
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] On July 30, 2009, Justin Gawronski, a US high school senior, and Antoine Bruguier, an American engineer, filed suit against Amazon in the United States District Court for the Western District of Washington.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] Bruguier argued that Amazon had violated its terms of service by remotely deleting the copy of *Nineteen Eighty-Four* he purchased, in the process preventing him from accessing annotations he had written.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] Gawronski's copy of the e-book was also deleted without his consent, and found Amazon used deceit in an email exchange.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] The complaint, which sought class-action status, asked for both monetary and injunctive relief.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] The case was settled on September 25, 2009, with Amazon agreeing to pay $150,000 divided between the two plaintiffs, on the understanding that the law firm representing them, Kamber Edelson, "will donate its portion of that fee to a charitable organization".
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] On September 4, 2009, Amazon offered all affected users a choice of restoring of the deleted e-books or receiving an Amazon gift certificate or check for US$30.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] In December 2010, Amazon removed three e-books written by Selena Kitt, along with works by several other self-published erotic fiction authors, for "offensive" content regarding consensual incest that violated Amazon's publishing guidelines.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] Kitt stated her opinion this Amazon policy was selectively applied to some books but not others that feature similar themes.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] For what Amazon describes as "a brief period of time", the books were unavailable for redownload by users who had already purchased them.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] This ability was restored after it was brought to Amazon's attention; however, no remote deletion took place.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] In October 2012, Amazon suspended the account of a Norwegian woman who purchased her Kindle in the United Kingdom, and the company deleted every e-book on her Kindle.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] Amazon claimed that she had violated their terms of service but did not specify what she had done wrong.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] After the woman contacted the media, Amazon restored her account and her purchased e-books.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] Since 2012, Amazon has sold e-books in China and later began selling the Kindle e-book readers from 2013 onwards.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] Amazon had also announced that it has sold several million Kindles in the country and that China became the world's biggest regional market for the Kindle in 2016.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] However, it was reported that Chinese consumers prefer using their smartphones over e-readers, notwithstanding competition from Tencent, Alibaba, JD.com and Douban, each with their own e-book readers or marketplaces.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] Domestically developed e-book readers from brands like Xiaomi, iReader and Onyx Boox also offer added competition to the Kindle.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] In 2022, Amazon announced it had stopped selling its Kindles to distributors in China and stated the online bookstore service would shut down in China on June 30, 2023.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] On January 4, 2022, a Kindle shortage was reported on Amazon's JD.com flagship store.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] Only the Kindle 10 had remained available for sale while other models like the Paperwhite, Oasis and Kids Edition had become out of stock.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] On the same day, It was announced that Amazon had also shut its Tmall flagship store, after having already closed its Kindle flagship store on Taobao earlier in October 2021.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] These led to speculation that Amazon was planning to exit the Chinese market altogether, although an official Amazon representative responded that they remain committed to serving Chinese consumers and they can continue to purchase the Kindle through offline and third-party online retailers.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] In June 2022, Amazon announced that it will shut down its Kindle bookstore in China and starting July 2023 Kindle users can no longer purchase online books in the country.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] However, existing customers could still download previously bought titles until June 2024.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] Also in June 2022, self-published authors protested against Amazon's e-book return policy; whenever an e-book return is made, royalties originally paid to the author at the time of purchase are deducted from their earnings balance, leaving authors with negative balances.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] In April 2026, Amazon announced the end of support for 13 early models on May 20, 2026.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] While it wouldn't make the devices entirely unusable (bricked), it would greatly reduce functionality, such as library e-book access via Libby.
[src:a-greek-english-lexicon/amazon-kindle] Shortly before the end date, consumer advocates USPIRG, longtime opponents of e-waste, launched an online petition campaign to press Amazon to keep the devices - many with batteries and screens quite functional - alive or allow third-party options.
